Scientific Question: Do the genes and proteins that are used for the UV-repair pathway in humans (specifically in nucleotide excision repair) have a high correlation in terms of nucleotide sequence similarity and protein structures with each other?¶

Background Information: There are two main categories of nucleotide excision repair: global genome nucleotide excision repair (GG-NER), and transcription-coupled nucleotide excision repair (TC-NER)(Araujo and Kuraoka, 2019). These categories do not correlate that much with each other as the proteins do not have more similar functions when compared to other ones in the same category. I want to know if the genes and structure of proteins with similar functions will have an increased similarity.

I found the genes and proteins responsible for NER on a separate website (https://www.mdanderson.org/documents/Labs/Wood-Laboratory/human-dna-repair-genes.html). I used NCBI and PDB to find the genes of interest and downloaded the gene files (.fasta format) necessary through NCBI (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/) and protein files(.pdb format) PDB (https://www.rcsb.org/). I used the genes ERCC2,ERCC3,XPC,XPA, GTF2H1, GTF2H2, XAB2, and LIG1 as my genes/proteins of interest. XPC and XPA both bind DNA. ERCC2 and ERCC3 both are helicases that move in the opposite direction. LIG1 is responsible for DNA ligase. GTF2H1 and GTF2H2 both make up the human core TFIIH. XAB2 is a pre-MRNA splicing factor. I used a pairwise sequence analysis to compare the nucleotide sequence between the different genes and a heatmap to plot them. I also used PyMol to visualize the genes from the PDB database. I also created a distancefinder function that shows the distance between two of the furthest atoms on a protein, which would ultimately be used to help compare the proteins structurally.

Arajo SJ, Kuraoka I. Nucleotide excision repair genes shaping embryonic development. Open Biol. 2019 Oct 31;9(10):190166. doi: 10.1098/rsob.190166. Epub 2019 Oct 30. PMID: 31662099; PMCID: PMC6833223.

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31662099/

Hypothesis: If the proteins, and thus genes, responsible for nucleotide excision repair have some similar functions to each other, then the proteins and the genes responsible for them in nucleotide excision repair will have the highest sequence and structural (specifically in terms of size) homology in relation to the ones that share the same functions.¶

If my hypothesis should be correct, then we should XPC be the most similar with XPA; ERCC2 should be the most similar to ERCC3; GTF2H1 should be the most similar to GTF2H2; and LIG1 and XAB2 could be similar to any or all of them but should not be almost identical to any because of their different functions.

Part 2: Pairwise Sequence Alignment¶

Pairwise sequence alignment compares the individual nucleotides in the different genes with each other. Once done, you end up with a pairwise alignment score that shows how many nucleotides matched with each other. In the code I read in the nucleotide sequence of the genes in a fasta file in order to be compared for pairwise sequence alignment. The function uses a method called pairwise2.align.globalxx that is used to create a number and have the number assigned as an integer to a new numpy array. The array will then be converted to a heatmap in order to visualize the data.

In [208]:
#Reads in the fasta file using SeqIO, Fasta is a global variable that contains the nucleotides of the different nucleotides
#SeqIO is used to convert the nucleotide sequence in the fasta file into readable and processable data as a list
#the fasta file was created using NCBI
Fasta = list(SeqIO.parse("DataFiles.fasta", "fasta"))
#Sets global variable size to the length of Fasta to be used in a for loop that runs through the entire list
size = len(Fasta)
#code check below
#print(size)

#creates empty array of (size,size) as the global variable 'alignments_score'  
alignments_score = np.empty(shape=(size,size))

#function that is a nested for loop to do pairwise sequence alignment with arguments 'my_numpy_array' and 'size'
def pairwise_seq_heatmap(my_numpy_array, size):
#for loop
    for i in range(size):
#for loop
        for j in range(size):
        # x,y are local variables that only reads the nucleotide sequence from the list
            X = Fasta[i].seq
            Y = Fasta[j].seq
            # Code Check below
            #print(Fasta[i].id)
            
            #my_numpy_array is a newly created array that contains the global alignment scores and is a local variable
            #the package NumPy is useful for creating new forms of data storage like arrays and also contains many array functions
            my_numpy_array[i,j] = int(pairwise2.align.globalxx(X, Y, score_only=True))
    #returns array
    return my_numpy_array
#calls the function 'pairwise_seq_heatmap' and sets 'My_alignment_scores' as the output as a global variable 
My_alignment_Scores = pairwise_seq_heatmap(alignments_score, size)
#code check
print(My_alignment_Scores)

Part 5 Finding the maximum "height" of the protein¶

Because looking at a static 2D image with 3D proteins cannot prove or quantify protein similarity, I wrote a function that helps with identifying the max distance of any two atoms with each other in each protein. This helps to better visualize the differences in size of the proteins. These distances will then be compared to each other in order to determine structural similarity. I could not get two of the protein data to load/be read. The two that could not load were the medium sized proteins (LIG1 and ERCC2). I read in the data by downloading the pdb files from https://www.rcsb.org/. I used Bio.PDB as the main package in order to read the protein data and have each atom/residue/protein contain its own data. Specifically I looked at every labeled atom's coordinates and found the distances from each other. The max distance is the farthest apart any two atoms are in the protein and is thus the maximum "height" of the protein.

#creates function distancefinder to find max distance with argument 'protein'
def distancefinder(protein):
    #creates local variables i to reset future while loop
    i=0    
    #creates local variable maxdistance to find the max distance
    #it is set as 0 initially before any two points are compared
    maxdistance=0
    #makes residue_list which is a list of all the Object residues in the argument as a local variable
    residue_list=Selection.unfold_entities(protein, "R")
    #creates local variable newlist as an empty list to add the residue id number, because residue_list returns an object Residue
    #I need to find the id number as a str or int to be able to use it to find distances, in this case I converted it to int
    #I will use newlist later as the index of the protein structure to identify each atom and thus the atom's coordinates
    newlist=[]
    #creates local variable idnumber to add to newlist as the id number
    idnumber=0
    #while loop that goes through the entire residue_list
    while i < (len(residue_list)):
        #loops until the code matches the residue seqID with the local variable idnumber
        #idnumber increases until it matches the seqID; once it matches, it is added into newlist and resets to 0 to start over
        if(repr(residue_list[i]).find("resseq="+str(idnumber)+" ")== -1):
            idnumber+=1
        else:
            newlist.append(j)
            idnumber=0
            i+=1
    #code check; newlist is now completed with all of the residue's seqIDs in order to be able to find the atoms' coordinates
    #print(newlist)
    
    #two for loops to find the distance between all possible pairs of atoms
    for m in range(len(newlist)):
         for n in range(len(newlist)):
            try:
                #asks if the distance between the two atoms is greater than the max distance
                #protein[0]["A"][newlist[m]]["CA"] calls for the atom's coordinates at the residue with that seqID
                if (protein[0]["A"][newlist[m]]["CA"]-protein[0]["A"][newlist[n]]["CA"])>maxdistance:
                    #sets maxdistance to the new distance
                    maxdistance=protein[0]["A"][newlist[m]]["CA"]-protein[0]["A"][newlist[n]]["CA"]
                    #code check; max distance can only increase since it is only changed when the new distance is greater than it
                    #print(maxdistance)
            except:
                pass
    #returns maxdistance        
    return maxdistance

#prints max distances of the different Proteins

Analyzing results¶

The heatmap successfully shows the pairwise sequence alignment comparisons between the different nucleotide sequences. I had the pairwise sequence alignment do around the first 20,000 nucleotides of all genes because it would be an easier comparison as a more diverse number would be a little harder to follow visually because the color variance; however, XAB2 only had around 10,000 nucleotides, so I could not change it to 20,000. The heatmap shows no definite correlation between any two or more different genes and their nucleotide sequences. The diagonals are the brightest and constant because those are the ones in which it compares the sequences to itself, showing the total amount of nucleotides that were used for comparison. All the rest of the heap is almost the exact same color throughout the heatmap except for XAB2; this is because of its smaller sample size of comparison. Taking XAB2's smaller number of nucleotides into account, this suggests that my hypothesis is incorrect in that there are no two or more genes that have a higher correlation or sequence homology with each other because each row and column have a constant color.

The distancefinder function shows the six proteins' maxdistance. Contrastingly, XAB2, which has the smallest number of nucleotides by far, is the largest protein by a significant margin. Although the data could not load in for LIG1 and ERCC2, one can visually see with the help of PyMOL imaging that LIG1 and ERCC2 are a little bigger or at the very least, a similar size to ERCC3. Based on the distances, XPA's most similar protein is ERCC3 and vice versa. XPC's most similar protein is GTF2H1 and vice versa. GTF2H2's size is close to GTF2H1's but is ultimately closest to ERCC3. XAB2 is an outlier and is not similar with any other genes. Note that the numbers given are unitless because they are given in a coordinate system; however, they are still accurate in the max "height" relative to each other. Based on the visual image given by PyMOL, one can also predict that LIG1's most similar protein is ERCC2 and vice versa in terms of size. If my hypothesis were correct, then XPA should have been the most similar in both nucleotide sequence and structure to XPC because they both function to bind damaged DNA. ERCC2 also should have been the most similar to ERCC3 because they both function to unwind the double stranded DNA. Lastly, GTF2H2 should have been most similar to GTF2H1 because they both function as part of the human TFIIH core complex. XAB2 did not share any functions with the other genes tested but was also extremely different in terms of the nucleotide sequence number and its protein size. My hypothesis turned out to be incorrect in that both the nucleotide sequence similarity and structural similarity did not correlate with the functions of the proteins.
